    <p>Placeholder images, stock photos, and media manipulation are crucial for web design and development.</p>

    <h3>5.1 Unsplash API</h3>
    <p>The Unsplash API provides access to the world's most powerful photo engine. The free tier allows 50 requests per hour, perfect for non-production applications.</p>

    <h3>5.2 Pexels API</h3>
    <p>Similar to Unsplash, Pexels offers a free API for accessing high-quality stock photos and videos with generous rate limits (200 requests per hour).</p>

    <h3>5.3 Lorem Picsum</h3>
    <p>The "Lorem Ipsum" for photos. It provides a simple URL-based API to fetch random placeholder images of specific dimensions. No API key required.</p>

    <h3>5.4 Cloudinary</h3>
    <p>Cloudinary is a powerful image and video management service. The free tier includes 25 monthly credits, which covers storage, transformations, and bandwidth for small projects.</p>

    <h3>5.5 The Cat API / The Dog API</h3>
    <p>Essential for testing and fun side projects, these APIs provide random pictures of cats and dogs. Completely free to use.</p>

    <p><em>Discover more tools in our <a href="/free-image-apis">Free Image APIs</a> article.</em></p>

    <h2>6. Authentication Services</h2>
    <p>Implementing secure authentication from scratch is difficult. These services provide robust APIs and SDKs.</p>

    <h3>6.1 Auth0</h3>
    <p>Auth0 by Okta offers a comprehensive identity management platform. The free tier supports up to 7,500 active users and unlimited logins.</p>

    <h3>6.2 Clerk</h3>
    <p>Clerk provides drop-in UI components and APIs for user authentication and management. The free tier includes 10,000 monthly active users, making it a favorite among Next.js and React developers.</p>

    <h3>6.3 Supabase Auth</h3>
    <p>Supabase provides an open-source alternative to Firebase. Its authentication module is fully integrated with its Postgres database and is free for up to 50,000 monthly active users.</p>

    <h3>6.4 Firebase Authentication</h3>
    <p>Google's Firebase offers a generous free tier for authentication, supporting phone numbers, passwords, and identity providers like Google, Facebook, and Twitter.</p>

    <p><em>Compare these providers in our <a href="/free-auth-services">Free Auth Services</a> guide.</em></p>

    <h2>7. Database Services (DBaaS)</h2>
    <p>Modern applications require scalable databases. Here are the best free-tier database services.</p>

    <h3>7.1 Supabase (PostgreSQL)</h3>
    <p>As an open-source Firebase alternative, Supabase offers a generous free tier including a 500MB PostgreSQL database, API, and authentication.</p>

    <h3>7.2 PlanetScale (MySQL)</h3>
    <p>PlanetScale is a serverless MySQL platform. While they recently adjusted their free tier, it remains an excellent choice for modern serverless architectures with its branching workflow.</p>

    <h3>7.3 Neon (Serverless Postgres)</h3>
    <p>Neon separates storage and compute to offer a truly serverless Postgres experience. The free tier includes 500MB of storage and a compute endpoint that scales to zero.</p>

    <h3>7.4 MongoDB Atlas</h3>
    <p>For NoSQL needs, MongoDB Atlas offers an M0 Free Cluster with 512MB of storage, shared RAM, and no credit card required.</p>

    <h3>7.5 Upstash (Redis / Kafka)</h3>
    <p>Upstash provides serverless data for Redis and Kafka. The free tier is request-based (up to 10,000 requests per day), ideal for caching and rate-limiting side projects.</p>

    <p><em>Find the right database in our <a href="/free-database-services">Free Database Services</a> overview.</em></p>

    <h2>Understanding and Managing API Rate Limits</h2>
    <p>When working with free APIs, the most common hurdle developers face is rate limiting. Rate limits dictate how many requests you can make to an API within a specific timeframe (e.g., requests per second, hour, or month).</p>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Common Rate Limit Headers</h3>
      <p>APIs typically communicate your usage limits via HTTP response headers:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>X-RateLimit-Limit</code>: The maximum number of requests permitted in the current time window.</li>
        <li><code>X-RateLimit-Remaining</code>: The number of requests remaining in the current window.</li>
        <li><code>X-RateLimit-Reset</code>: The time at which the current rate limit window resets.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p>To avoid hitting these limits and causing application failures, consider the following strategies:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Implement Caching:</strong> Store API responses locally (e.g., in memory or using Redis) for a set period. If a user requests the same data, serve the cached version instead of hitting the API again.</li>
      <li><strong>Use Request Queues:</strong> If your application needs to make bulk requests, place them in a queue and process them at a controlled rate that respects the API's limits.</li>
      <li><strong>Exponential Backoff:</strong> If you receive a <code>429 Too Many Requests</code> response, do not immediately retry. Instead, wait for a short period (e.g., 1 second) before retrying. If it fails again, double the wait time (2 seconds, 4 seconds, etc.).</li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>For a deep dive into implementation strategies, read our <a href="/api-rate-limit-guide">API Rate Limiting Guide</a>.</em></p>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>The ecosystem of free APIs in 2026 is richer than ever, providing developers with the tools to build sophisticated applications without upfront costs. By combining these services—using Supabase for your database, Clerk for authentication, and various specialized APIs for features—you can architect robust platforms on a budget. Always remember to monitor your usage, implement proper caching, and respect the rate limits to ensure your applications run smoothly.</p>

